ntended. &#10;It could. And there are lots of potential solutions to the issue if it arrises.&#10;In addition to all the things MrsCayne mentioned, you might even have the option to place your child back in school for some of those subjects. &#10;I think I'm lucky here in Maine. The way it's set up is that I can place my kids in school for individual subjects if I like. The schools seem very willing to help facilitate this, I think in part because it helps them obtain more funding. So, I hate math. Struggled with it. Wouldn't be the best teacher for my kids once we got past the basics. I can enroll them back in public school for just that class, and continue to do the rest of the schooling at home. &#10;Same with all the other subjects, sports programs, after school activities, etc."/><type4:DocumentMetaData xmi:id="13" sofa="1" begin="0" end="1084" language="en" documentId="483" isLastSegment="false"/><types:WebArgumentMetadata xmi:id="24" sofa="1" begin="0" end="0" author="Semi-Crunchy-Dad" date="09/04/2013" docType="forumpost" origUrl="http://community.babycenter.com/post/a44369503/home_schooling_debate_this_hypothetical?cpg=6" topic="homeschooling" thumbsUp="0" thumbsDown="0" origId="483" notes="" title="Home schooling: Debate this hypothetical"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="39" sofa="1" begin="0" end="316"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="43" sofa="1" begin="317" end="396"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="47" sofa="1" begin="397" end="541"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="51" sofa="1" begin="542" end="1003"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="55" sofa="1" begin="1004" end="1084"/><cas:View sofa="1" members="13 24 39 43 47 51 55"/></xmi:XMI>